You can achieve this by implementing a property with the same name that returns different values based on the data type of the parameter passed to the property. Here's an example:

```
public class Time
{
    private int _minutes;

    // Constructor
    public Time(int minutes)
    {
        _minutes = minutes;
    }

    // Property with the same name that returns different values
    public dynamic Value
    {
        get
        {
            return _minutes / 60.0; // returns double if asked by double
        }
        set
        {
            if (value is double)
            {
                _minutes = (int)(value * 60);
            }
            else if (value is int)
            {
                _minutes = (int)value; // returns int if asked for int
            }
            else
            {
                throw new ArgumentException("Invalid data type");
            }
        }
    }
}
```

With this implementation, you can create a `Time` object and set its `Value` property with either a `double` or an `int`. When you ask for the property as `double`, it will return the hour value and when you ask for it as an `int`, it will return the minute value. Here's an example usage of the `Time` class:

```
Time t = new Time(90);
Console.WriteLine(t.Value); // Output: 1.5 (double)
t.Value = 120;
Console.WriteLine(t.Value); // Output: 120 (int)
```

In the above example, the first `Console.WriteLine` statement outputs the hour value because the `Value` property is accessed as `double`. The second statement outputs the minute value because the `Value` property is accessed as `int`.

