In your case, the value of `Entrada` is currently a `double` (since it was last set with a `double` value), so the `+` operator will be resolved as a dynamic addition between a `double` and an `int`. This can produce unexpected results, as you've seen.

To avoid this dynamic behavior, you can either:

1. Cast the result of the property getter to `int` before applying the `+` operator, like this:

   ```
   Console.WriteLine((int)Entrada + 10);
   ```

   This will cast the `Entrada` property value to an `int` before adding 10, which should produce the expected result of 310.

2. Alternatively, you can consider changing the property type from `dynamic` to a specific type, such as `int` or `double`. This will give you more control over the behavior of the property and will avoid dynamic dispatch at runtime.

