No, you cannot define two properties with the same name and different types in the same class in C#. This is because the C# language considers the name of the property to be part of its signature, which must be unique within a class.

Instead, you might consider using two different property names that are explicitly related to their respective units of measurement. For example:

```
public class TimeEntry
{
    private int _minutes;

    public int Minutes 
    { 
        get { return _minutes; } 
        set { _minutes = value; } 
    }

    public double Hours 
    { 
        get { return _minutes / 60.0; } 
        set { _minutes = (int)(value * 60); } 
    }
}
```

In this implementation, the `TimeEntry` class defines two properties, `Minutes` and `Hours`, that are explicitly labeled with their respective units of measurement. The `Minutes` property is used to set and retrieve the time value in minutes, while the `Hours` property is used to set and retrieve the time value in hours. 

Using this approach, you can set and get the time value in the units that are most appropriate for your code at any given time, without having to perform any manual conversions or casts. For example:

```
var timeEntry = new TimeEntry();
timeEntry.Hours = 1.5;  // Sets the time to 1.5 hours
Console.WriteLine(timeEntry.Minutes);  // Output: 90
Console.WriteLine(timeEntry.Hours);  // Output: 1.5
timeEntry.Minutes = 120;  // Sets the time to 120 minutes
Console.WriteLine(timeEntry.Minutes);  // Output: 120
Console.WriteLine(timeEntry.Hours);  // Output: 2.0
```

Using this approach makes your code more readable and self-explanatory, and removes the ambiguity and potential errors caused by using a single property with a dynamic type.

Yes, you can define the `TimeEntry` class as a struct instead of a class. Structs in C# are value types that have similar behavior to classes but are allocated on the stack instead of the heap.

Here's an example implementation of `TimeEntry` as a struct:

```
public struct TimeEntry
{
    private int _minutes;

    public int Minutes 
    { 
        get { return _minutes; } 
        set { _minutes = value; } 
    }

    public double Hours 
    { 
        get { return _minutes / 60.0; } 
        set { _minutes = (int)(value * 60); } 
    }
}
```

The usage of this struct would be similar to the class implementation:

```
var timeEntry = new TimeEntry();
timeEntry.Hours = 1.5;  // Sets the time to 1.5 hours
Console.WriteLine(timeEntry.Minutes);  // Output: 90
Console.WriteLine(timeEntry.Hours);  // Output: 1.5
timeEntry.Minutes = 120;  // Sets the time to 120 minutes
Console.WriteLine(timeEntry.Minutes);  // Output: 120
Console.WriteLine(timeEntry.Hours);  // Output: 2.0
```

The main difference between a struct and a class is that a struct is a value type and is allocated on the stack, while a class is a reference type and is allocated on the heap. This has implications for how the struct is used and how it interacts with other parts of your code, but for a small struct like `TimeEntry` it shouldn't have a significant impact on performance or behavior.

