The EndPrint event of the PrintDocument object is called when the printing is complete or when an error has occurred. This event does not provide any indication of whether the printing was successful or cancelled by the user.

To detect if the printing was successful or cancelled, you can use the PrintPage event of the PrintDocument object. This event is called for each page that is printed, and you can keep track of the page count to determine if all pages were printed successfully.

Here's an example of how you can use the PrintPage event to detect if the printing was successful or cancelled:

```csharp
int pageCount = 0;
bool printingCancelled = false;

void PrintDocument(PrintDocument printDoc)
{
    pageCount = 0;
    printingCancelled = false;

    printDoc.PrintPage += new PrintPageEventHandler(PrintPageHandler);

    // Show the print dialog
    PrintDialog printDlg = new PrintDialog();
    if (printDlg.ShowDialog() == DialogResult.OK)
    {
        printDoc.PrinterSettings = printDlg.PrinterSettings;
        printDoc.Print();
    }

    printDoc.PrintPage -= new PrintPageEventHandler(PrintPageHandler);

    if (!printingCancelled && pageCount > 0)
    {
        // Printing was successful
    }
}

void PrintPageHandler(object sender, PrintPageEventArgs e)
{
    // Print the page
    // ...

    pageCount++;

    if (e.Cancel)
    {
        printingCancelled = true;
    }
}
```

In this example, the PrintPage event handler updates the pageCount variable for each page that is printed. If the event is cancelled by the user, the printingCancelled variable is set to true.

After the printing process is complete, the code checks if the printing was cancelled and if any pages were printed. If the printingCancelled variable is false and the pageCount is greater than 0, then it assumes that the printing was successful.

